{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778550917,"nonce":"5v63AEz3cgFqYXG/3YTIcF7AmUs=","message":"**Implementation in progress** — feature/worktree-shared-artifacts\n\nImplementing option (d): adding `.worktree.yaml` with `_artifacts` in `shared:`.\n\nDiscovered during implementation: the existing tracked file `_artifacts/README.md` (re-included in `.gitignore` via `!_artifacts/README.md`) conflicts with the symlink approach. When `wt` creates a worktree, `git checkout` materializes the tracked README, then `wt` removes the `_artifacts/` directory and replaces it with a symlink. The symlink resolves to the README's content fine (via main's `_artifacts/README.md`), but git in the worktree then sees `_artifacts/README.md` as \"deleted\" because the path now lives \"beyond a symbolic link\". This dirties every new worktree permanently and blocks `wt-merge` (which requires a clean worktree).\n\nResolution: also untrack `_artifacts/README.md` (`git rm --cached`) and simplify the gitignore block to `_artifacts` (no trailing slash, no re-include exception). The README file stays on disk in main and remains accessible from every worktree via the symlink. New clones will not have the README, but the same documentation lives in CLAUDE.md.\n\nAlso: the gitignore pattern needs to be `_artifacts` without a trailing slash, otherwise the `_artifacts` symlink itself (which is a symbolic-link file, not a directory) shows as untracked.\n\nVerified the symlink mechanism works: from the feature worktree, manually running the same `ln -sfn` operation that `wt-sync` performs creates `worktree/_artifacts -\u003e main/_artifacts`, README content reads correctly through the symlink, and `git status` shows only the intended changes.","files":null}]}